# Webspace testing (Seismo 0.5)

The 0.5 consolidation is **validated on the user's actual webspace**, not only locally. Each slice ends with an upload + live smoke test before the next slice starts.

## Hard rules

- **0.4 keeps running as the reference.** On the user's host the actual layout is **0.5 at `/seismo/`** (the stable, user-facing URL) and **0.4 at `/seismo-staging/`** (the living fallback). Never touch `/seismo-staging/` from 0.5 work — it exists so we can diff live behaviour against the new code at any time.
- **No destructive DB operations** in any slice that ships to the shared host, unless the user has explicitly confirmed a backup or a dedicated test DB. Read-only slices may point at the existing 0.4 DB; schema-changing slices MUST use a fresh DB or an explicit, reversible migration.
- **`config.local.php` is created on the server**, never committed, never uploaded with real credentials from the dev machine. Ship the `.example` file; the user (or wizard) fills it in on the host.
- **No FTP automation by the agent.** The agent prepares a concrete, copy-pasteable upload list per slice and the user performs the upload. Never assume a deploy path that hasn't been confirmed.

## What every slice must produce

1. A **one-line test URL** the user can open (e.g. `https://<host>/seismo_0.5/?action=health`).
2. A **checklist of expected output** for that URL (dbStatus ok, schema version, mode, etc.).
3. An **upload list** showing exactly which files/folders to transfer, and which to skip (`.git`, `.cursor`, most of `docs/` except **always** `docs/db-schema.sql` when `migrate.php` is part of the slice — the migrator reads it at runtime).
4. A **rollback note**: what the user does if the slice misbehaves (usually "delete `/seismo_0.5/`; 0.4 is untouched").

## Portability bugs found on the webspace

When something breaks on the host but works locally (path, header, PHP extension, mod_rewrite, session dir, …):

1. Fix it in 0.5 directly (don't re-exile it to 0.4).
2. **Append** the finding to `docs/setup-wizard-notes.md` so the future first-run wizard catches it.
3. If it affects 0.4 too, mirror the fix there with a short commit; don't leave the user on a broken mothership while 0.5 matures.

